svg:text.svg:tspan: The ambiguous wording of the Witches’ prophecies in Act 4, Scene 1 creates uncertainty
about what is true. Macbeth is told that he cannot be defeated by anyone “of woman born”,
which could mean ‘anyone’ or ‘someone who was born naturally’. Macbeth doesn’t see this
ambiguity, which makes him assume his victory is certain. In reality, the prophecies are
predicting his defeat by Macduff, who was born by Caesarean section. This shows how
the Witches use appearance to obscure reality, just as the Macbeths do. Despite Macbeth
hiding reality behind false appearances, he falls victim to a similar deception by the Witches.
This ironic twist shows that people who deceive others can be deceived themselves, which
emphasises that nothing can be trusted.
Shakespeare uses the Witches to present the distinction between appearance and
reality as blurred. In Act 1, Scene 1, the Witches chant “Fair is foul, and foul is fair”, which
implies that things which appear to be good are actually evil, and introduces the idea that
appearance may not reect reality. The metre emphasises this idea, as the stress placed
on “fair” and “foul” makes these words stand out, encouraging the audience to notice
the contrast between the two terms. This leads the audience to suspect that although
the Witches’ prophecies seem to promise great things for Macbeth, they are not what
they appear. As Shakespearean audiences believed witches were both real and evil, the
atmosphere of doom would have been heightened, as they would have expected the Witches
in ‘Macbeth’ to be disguising wicked intentions.
Shakespeare also uses Macbeth’s visions to create confusion between appearance
and reality. In Macbeth’s “Is this a dagger” soliloquy, he asks questions about whether the
dagger is “sensible / To feeling” or simply a “dagger of the mind”. While he can see the
dagger, he can’t touch it, which paradoxically suggests that it is both real and imaginary.
Shakespeare’s use of paradox here increases the already-established confusion over the line
between appearance and reality. The staging of the visions further adds to this confusion.
Banquo’s ghost usually appears on-stage, so the audience, like Macbeth, cannot tell if it
is real or imaginary. The audience’s inability to make this distinction reinforces how easily
appearance and reality may be confused.
The world of ‘Macbeth’ is one in which things aren’t as they seem. Shakespeare uses
language to show how vastly different appearance can be from reality, and how this can be
used to deceive others. Throughout the play, Shakespeare creates a complex and confusing
relationship between appearance and reality that leaves the characters and audience
questioning the reliability of everything they have experienced.
